Nutrition of Obese Children: No breakfast and sausage for dinner
More than one third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 weigh more than the norm; while 9 per cent of schoolchildren are overweight, 5 per cent suffer from obesity.
According to a recent study, children suffering from obesity usually come from families with an unhealthy lifestyle.
We see once again the importance of the environment and behaviours associated with a person for his or her healthy development.
For example, sausage appears on the tables of children suffering from obesity almost twice as often as in families with children of normal weight.
More than 19% of children suffering from obesity ate fries for dinner on the eve of an educational event called Obesity is no accident.
Moreover, families of children suffering from obesity do not engage in sports, but this is true for most families of modern schoolchildren - only 15 per cent of children said that their parents find time to exercise at least once a week.
The study was conducted among 900 children.
The study was conducted at the end of the last school year, with almost 900 pupils attending elementary classes throughout Bohemia.
Obesity was not an accident for the second consecutive year, with the support of the insurance company Všeobecná zdravotní pojişōvna and Unilever.
So far, more than 12,000 students in grades 4 to 8 have joined the project.
Adequate nutrition and sufficient sporting burdens are the main determinants of the rapidly growing number of children who suffer from either overweight or obesity.
"For example, only half of those interviewed said they eat five times a day, according to the breakfast-dinner-dinner-dinner-dinner scheme, which is one of the essential conditions for proper nutrition," says one of the findings of the study.
No lunch and sausage in the evenings.
Experts warn that even relative details such as the constant time of family breakfast are important for healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of school-age families have breakfast together.
In most families, everyone eats breakfast separately.
The worst discovery was that in every tenth family, people don't eat breakfast at all.
Yet, breakfast is the basis of the right daily diet.
The study found that fried food is more commonly used in families with children suffering from obesity.
Almost everyone, regardless of weight, drinks sweet cool drinks every day (70%).
Although more than 40 per cent of children regularly participate in sports, this figure falls by more than half, to 15 per cent, when it comes to their parents.
Make your own menu.
In another part of the study, selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) were asked to draw up their own menu based on the products offered and based on their tastes and preferences.
"The food preferences of Czech children between the ages of 12 and 15 are far from the ideal of healthy nutrition".
Their favorite food includes a large number of flour, meat, and sweet foods.
"A particular concern is the high popularity of sweet cool drinks," says the final part of the study.
As the main lunch dish, the paste defeated the bird with a small margin.
However, children showed little interest in bean, fish and vegetable dishes.
Seeking a Healthy Lifestyle
The study also showed that children are willing to change their eating habits, provided that they are provided with relevant information.
"Many members of the test group have shown a significant shift in preferences towards healthy food when they filled out a questionnaire after the lecture was completed Obesity is not an accident," the project's outcome states.
This was particularly evident, for example, in the case of sweet cool drinks, with more children preferring just water to them.
In addition, children have more often mentioned poultry and fish as the main food, limiting the amount of sweet foods and pastries.
