V Need for Speed: Escape occurs in America.
Overview
What was supposed to be a carefree walk turned into a routine morning trip to work due to a series of totally inappropriate and careless mistakes.
Ambition to some extent was satisfied, but it doesn't matter, as no one clearly wanted to do extra work.
Before the release of the new version with the subheading "Escape", there was a lot of hope.
It was expected to move the previous series of Need For Speed in a new direction; the demonstration versions showed that the game would take a decent place in the racing genre.
We were curious to see parts of the game where the main character gets out of the car and runs.
As is often the case with NFS, in the end, much is different from what we expected.
The game is a fairly good arcade race, but the general impression is corrupted by a few unnecessary mistakes that have been present in this series of games for several years.
Which means, in reality, it's not a mistake, it's an unexplained lazy development.
The adventure begins very well.
You become part of a story whose main character, Jack, decides to solve some personal problems by participating in an illegal race through America.
You get in a car on the west coast, in San Francisco, and your job is to get to New York first.
This idea has some interesting features.
The route consists of ten stages divided into more than fifty races.
This means that each race goes along its own route, individual stages take place in a diverse and interesting environment.
So it doesn't feel like the same thing happens in the game all the time.
Although the graphs are at the same level as in previous parts of the series, it is nice to see some tracks.
Yet, the game does not give rise to strong emotions.
Although driving through the desert, it is a pleasure to drive through the autumn suburbs or high in the snowy mountains.
In addition, the race occasionally revives an unusual detail.
In the desert, for example, you are caught in a sandstorm that significantly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, the mountains need to be careful not to fall under the avalanche.
The individual races are quite well organized.
There are only a few varieties, but that's enough.
For a while you're trying to outrun several rivals (in essence a regular race); then you're trying to improve time (standard race with a secondomer); or you're competing with one opponent.
Among other things, you run into the police from time to time, which makes your task even more difficult.
The components outside the car are new.
It's just an interactive animation where most of the time Jack runs away from someone and you have to help him by pressing the right buttons at the right time.
It's no big deal.
Although surprising, these fragments are much smaller than you could expect (only three to be accurate).
In fact, it turns out to be good for the game because it's not boring; given all the above, it's one of the things that makes the game interesting.
The racing model is following the tracks of previous models.
This means that it is no longer something special, but it cannot be considered a deficiency.
If you're looking for a simulation of real life, you're going to have to look elsewhere.
Yet, this model of driving is very suitable for dynamic races, although better options can be found in the market.
So far, so good.
After a while, however, problems begin.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is not so good.
You don't expect complex transformations and confrontations from this game, but if you have no idea what your car is going to do before you hit an object, something's wrong.
Normally, overtaking or passing cars in a dense stream, you sometimes touch another car slightly, and yet sometimes in a virtually similar situation, your car starts to spin wildly.
Or she broke up.
It's not important because of the restart system, but it's enough to ruin the fun.
The restarts are designed so that if you break up or go far off the track, the game brings you back to the point where it stopped.
However, only five restarts are available for each race.
If you use them all, you'll have to start the race from the start.
It's helpful if something doesn't work out, but you can't rely entirely on it.
Sometimes restarts are not enough, and you have to learn by heart a separate section of the race.
An important shortcoming of the game is the fact that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some turns need to be made in a certain way, or you just won't fit in.
In other cases, you meet civilian vehicles in a certain location in the same configuration, regardless of whether you arrive first, fifth, five seconds early or a minute later.
This is particularly annoying in situations where you see your opponent easily passing between two cars moving in the opposite direction, whereas when you are there, cars are already positioned so that you need either to bypass them or to drop your speed.
It doesn't matter when you're near them; it's all arranged that the situation always happens right in front of your nose.
The rivals have other advantages.
During the game, you discover several places where, regardless of time, the same opponent overtakes you in the same place.
It's particularly obvious at the end of the game, on a long bridge where you're driving in the opposite direction.
Obviously, your opponent should stand before you no matter what.
The thing is, when he's driving in front of you, he's making you look worse, leading to one or more accidents on this site.
You can understand trying to make the game more interesting and filled with adrenaline, but it's so obvious that it's rapidly starting to cause irritation.
It's a shame, because despite a simple driving model, the game is interesting and sometimes so full of events that you don't have time to pay attention to what's going on around you.
It doesn't matter what keeps you from missing-- a concept with 50 unique tracks, a sequence of races or something.
The idea of changing cars during races is unusual.
You need to keep track of gas stations on the way, because that's where your car can switch, even though in most cases the one you already have is enough.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are suitable for cities; powerful American cars are for straight sections of the highway; and exotic super sportscars for technical driving, such as curved mountain tracks.
The main history mode is closely linked to the challenge mode mode; it is a race on individual plots that you will learn in the course of the game.
Here you win for your personal affairs both medals and points common to the Challenges and Story modes.
Many possibilities are available to obtain a higher level of driving, ranging from cars to profile data.
In addition, the profile is related to the online function of Autolog, which, among other things, compares your performance with that of other players, and provides communication to the public.
This is another weakness that is difficult to understand; it is an example from the last race in sequence.
You and your car enter the subway tunnel (let's say so) where you run on the tracks in the dark (let's say so).
Your speedometer shows numbers from 150 to 200 km/h (let's say so), when suddenly a subway train hits you from behind, turning your car into a pile of scrap metal.
For a few days, our editorials discussed whether no one really thought a second at the time of the game's creation, or whether its creators really think we're such jerks.
The technical component of the game is nothing special; but the overall impression from the video order is mostly pleasant, sometimes even amazing.
Although it is unfortunate that, at some critical moments, the quality of recording is sometimes quite high, it is declining.
This is particularly true of incidents involving a large number of participants, where a good recording would not help you very much, either.
Sound's fine; soundtrack's on the amateur.
To please as wide a youth audience as possible, songs from different styles have entered into the soundtrack; but it is unlikely that many people will buy the game because of its music.
The general impression of Need for Speed: The run is rather disorderly.
If the game avoided obviously unnecessary mistakes, we could honestly say that Escape is the best part of NFS in the last few years.
Anyway, the game leaves a sense of unfinished business.
Of course, it's a good entertainment, but prepare yourself for the defects to blind you as a searchlight for the airport.
