Brand History:
IBM's innovator enters the second century of its existence.
If anyone wants to find a word that best expresses IMB's strategy, the closest is likely to be "long-lasting."
For the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution; the company is considered to be very modern, although it was founded over a century ago.
The company's long-term viability was laid down by its first boss, dreamer Thomas J. Watson, Sr.
He believed in his motto that many of the world's problems could be easily solved if people wanted to think.
His slogan "Think!" thus became the stamp around which the life of the future giant unfolded (as well as the name of his internal magazine, which IMB began to publish in 1935).
Moreover, it was the foundation of the corporate culture Watson carefully built.
"For us in IBM, long-term thinking means a constant movement towards the future.
IBM survived and flourished for a hundred years because she remained faithful to her original values, though she was not afraid to change everything around herself.
In our first hundred years, this has allowed us to transform technology, business, and company.
In the second hundred years we hope to achieve even more," says current company manager Samuel J. Palmisano on the occasion of the anniversary.
Complex system
In the 1930s, Watson approached the issue of employee care just as Batya in the Czech Republic - IMB employees were among the first American employees with paid leave, employer insurance, elegant uniform, and a complex system of bonuses for the best inventors and entrepreneurs.
The long-term relationship of IBM with consumers is similarly advanced.
From the beginning, the company had been brilliantly used by talented people, one of the first companies in the world to eliminate all discrimination, which gave it an excellent choice.
Concurs with the anti-discrimination strategy and the current plan, according to which a woman, Virginia Rometti, will replace Palmisano next year.
She has worked for IBM for thirty years; she is currently Director of Sales, Marketing and Development.
For the past few years, IBM has organized meetings, online brainstorms, during which many future innovations emerge.
No wonder there's a lot of ideas - about half a million people working in the company.
Organization with a good reputation
The firm's strong position in business is ensured by strong internal and external image.
