History of IBM: From cheese knife to space missions.
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York 100 years ago, and its original name "Compilation Corporation, Tabulation, Records" was quite complex.
It took the name IBM in 1924, originally called the brand used for the company's offices in Canada and South America.
The foundations of the future IBM were laid by the merger of four companies whose history begins in the 1880s.
They possessed technologies such as legendary "tough watch", i.e. clocks recording the time when employees come and go to work.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlet Flint, who also headed the company's board of trustees until 1930.
Flint hired the director of the rival company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
The leader then moved the founder of IBM into the shadow - Watson's ideas remain the basis of an unshakeable corporate culture and individuality.
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM, as is clear from the title, started from the production and sale of various business equipment, ranging from cheese knives and meat cutters to cash machines.
In the first four years of Watson's leadership, revenue doubled to $9 million, and a large-scale expansion of the company to all continents began.
Watson became so important to the company that after almost forty years, his son, Thomas Watson Jr., took his seat in the director's chair.
Under his leadership, IBM began to develop artificial intelligence technologies and created the first programming language.
In the 1960s, both IBM staff and computers helped NASA monitor space missions to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969, a human flight to the Moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers, IBM line System/360.
A classic PC that defined computer standards at the time, called IBM 5150, appeared on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold the production of the computers to Lenovo, while buying the PricewaterhouseCoopers consulting office, thus entirely focusing on consulting and high-value-added services.
Over the past three years, IBM has made great strides with its concept of the Smart Planet.
Its objective is to make reasonable use of technology in areas where it has not yet been planned and to improve the road situation and urban management.
In the area of commerce, IBM recently introduced the Smart Commerce platform, which helps businessmen control the entire trading cycle.
IBM traditions are strong even in our country.
In the former Czechoslovakia, as the first country to be located simultaneously in central and eastern Europe, IBM founded its branch in 1932.
Today, IBM CZ also manages a strategic outsourcing centre in Brno.
Central and Eastern Europe is headquartered in Prague, where a world-level research group on speech recognition also operates.
