Architectural history with ups, downs and happy endings: Austria's pavilion for the 1958 World Exhibition in Brussels won prizes, became a museum in Vienna, was empty and was abandoned.
Now it's being reopened as an exhibition center.
The Austrian Pavilion, designed by Carl Schwanzer for the 1958 World Exhibition in Brussels, is a well-known example of modern post-war architecture with its simple forms, glass halls, which boldly expressed faith in technological progress.
Schwanzera Pavilion won the Grand Prix on Architecture in 1958 for its light floating steel and glass design.
The building is considered a milestone in modern architecture.
This made the architect so famous that he also built an Austrian pavilion at the next World Exhibition.
Eventually, he was famous for the world in 1973 for his legendary four-cylinder tower BMW and her sister, a bowl-shaped building.
The pavilion, conceived as a building for temporary exhibitions, was moved to the Swiss Garden near the Southern Station of Vienna, transformed and opened as the 20th-century Museum in 1962 - and is often referred to as the 20th-century House for this reason.
Anyway, the building was not suitable for the museum for technical and spatial reasons - there were no walls on which to hang works of art, and poor air conditioning.
However, it continued to be used until modern art in Vienna received a new home.
The house has been empty since 2001, and its condition has become worse and worse.
Architect Adolf Krishanitz has so far renovated the pavilion, which was named the 21st century House, and will be used as a museum of contemporary art.
This museum is a branch of the Belvedere Museum, which will open the first exhibition on Tuesday night - in every sense a joyous event.
Agnes Hussain-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Belveder Gallery in 2007, contributed to a new venture.
Hussain-Arco, a graduate of the Faculty of Art History with a brilliant career as a figure skater in youth who worked at Sotheby's, Guggenheim Museum and eventually became the founder and director of the Modernization Museum in Salzburg, convinced politicians and keepers to continue the renovation, attracted public funds and private donations, and decided how the building would be used.
The new museum was to accommodate a permanent exhibition of the Fritz Votruba foundation, a cafe and a bookstore, along with modern art, and an office building was to be built.
Strict Control & Limited Budget
Krishanitz was then the perfect candidate for the project.
He was known, of course, through the restoration and expansion of the Vienna Secession Josef Olbrich, and won the contest, but he also studied from Schwanzer at the University of Technology Vienna, and the pavilion was for him "a particularly important place" where he attended exhibitions "almost every week."
He knew the original design and knew the tasks that stood in front of the building, a building that had already lost part of its greatness and ease when it was moved to Vienna and transformed.
The problems with the last restructuring were much more serious, the building was an energy sink, says Krishanitz.
The window profiles on the glass facade were replaced, the glass reinforced safety glass was inserted, and the glass roof was replaced by a high-end safe glass.
Steel crossovers of the thermal bridge were reinforced or replaced, and asbestos was removed from the ceilings.
Two lower floors created space for the new use of the building, a fallen light well between the building and the street provides lighting - a virtually new building but still a fine Schwanzer Pavilion.
Original exterior doors were retained, and the building was painted into an old red-brown color of corrosion protection.
The theater hall is the same as it used to be.
These are all subject to strict control by the museum office and with a limited budget.
"We often had to find material that was good, cheap and approved by the museum office," says Krishanitz, pointing to the uneven floor in the basement.
The building remained flexible and light despite limitations, problems, and transformation.
Krishanitz recently noticed that the Brussels pavilion was a rough, typical story of "crawling in the city."
This architecture is "always out of place" and still wants to "encourage real awareness."
The 21st century house is in a very right place, because in planning the city, there was unexpected luck, and a completely reconstructed "head station quarter" with offices and residential properties is growing around the Swiss Garden.
A second happy event may occur. The 21st century house may be supplemented by the second Krishanitz building, collector Francesca von Habsburg, has acquired the Berlin Temporary Exhibition Hall and is reportedly negotiating with the city about its location next door in the Swiss Garden.
