Peter Englund's busy and very kind new book, Beauty and Grief: The Personal History of World War I, begins with a long list of actors from which the heart dies.
Here's the advice to read next: carefully cut out this page and use it as a bookmark.
You will meet these people very closely as Mr. Englund's story goes, and this list of actors will be your GPS, your beacon, at times when, like one of these men and women, you'll get lost in the fog of war.
Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new Permanent Secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
The book he wrote now is unusual, he describes it, quite precisely, as "work on anti-historical history."
It has few known names, important treaties, or famous battles; there are almost no ambassadors, cunning journalists, or discussions on tactics and military equipment.
It's not so much a book about what was, he explains, as a book about what it was like, it's about "feelings, impressions, experiences, and state of the spirit."
The book Beauty and Grievance combined the experiences of the military years of 20 more or less insignificant men and women, from both sides of the front line, from schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and employees.
Some of these people will become heroes.
Someone gets captured, loses a hand or a leg, goes crazy or dies.
Their lives are glimmering here like church candles: new ones are added to a multitude of others, and some are extinguished at this time.
Mr. Englund's book is a departure from the standard of historical books.
This is an amendment to the notion that World War I was only a severe trenches war on the Western Front.
Beauty and Grief ably provides a panoramic of other theatres of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
The soldiers in this book are hit by bee hives; one of them meets Christmas in Egypt under pyramids; the unresolved problem is tsetse flies.
It's an exciting book, almost from the beginning.
The war covers the lives of these people like a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina, smelling like smokeless powder.
When a canonade is heard and you're a woman and you're at home with the children, will you stay where you are or will you run away?
Anyway, who's coming?
Almost no one understands what's going on or why we have to fight this war.
"The lack of facts," Mr. Englund notes, "replete with speculations, assumptions, hopes, fears, obsessions, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors."
Beauty and sorrow tracks the fate of people like Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor of the German High Seas Fleet.
Their stories are taken mainly from memoirs, letters and other materials already published.
Stories about their lives may be scary or exciting, but they are highly alive due to the small moments and fragmentary details collected by Mr. Englund.
Many of them are about deprivation and how to deal with it.
Telling the story of a German schoolgirl, he says, "Erzac, everywhere is Erzac."
"Coffee substitute, fake aluminum, fake rubber, paper bandages, wooden buttons".
He continues to talk about erzatz food in Germany.
He describes "a meat of pressed rice welded in lamb fat (and decorated with a fake bone made of wood); tobacco made of dried roots and dried potato skin; shoes hit by a tree".
He notes that there were “837 registered substitutes for meat permitted in sausage production, 511 registered substitutes for coffee”.
Some stories tell of honour and courage.
One American notes in himself the desire for cruelty and says of war: "You feel that, after all, this is what men were created for, not to sit in comfortable chairs with cigarettes and whiskey, an evening newspaper or a bestseller, and to claim that this display is civilization and under your decorated cufflinked shirt there is no barbarian."
On the contrary, the British soldier observes that he is likely to die and no one will notice or grieve.
"When a person comes to terms with the idea of self-sacrifice, he would like to think it would happen in front of the public," he writes.
But on the contrary, it's like a "sentenced man hanged in secret."
Other comments concern old Europe, which is falling apart, and new forms of fear.
"Conflict became an increasingly economic competition," Mr. Englund writes, "war factories."
He notices the coming of someone he calls "a new species in the bestaries of the beginning of the century: a beautifully expressed and ideologically convinced mass murderer in a well-sewn suit that arranges a massacre sitting at a written table."
People act in an unanticipated way: low-level acts are as much heroic as heroism.
Mr. Englund spoke of soldiers who tried their best to catch sexually transmitted diseases from prostitutes in order to avoid serving on the front.
"The most grotesque expression of this can be seen in the gonore pus trade that the soldiers bought and smeared their genitals in the hope of getting to the hospital," he writes.
"All the desperate rubbed him in the eye, which often led to lifelong blindness".
Translated with Swedish Peter Graves, Mr. Englund's prose is flexible, but unscrupulous, well suited to his humanistic task.
In dozens of small scenes, he shows how war "frees completely uncontrolled forces: extreme nationalism, social revolution, religious hatred."
People are starting to wonder why their leaders are forcing them to fight.
The best books about World War I were often indirect, such as Paul Fassel's Great War and Modern Memory or novels such as Erich-Marie Remark's Western Front Without Change, rather than exhaustive historical writings.
Mr. Englund's book is part of this uncharted pantheon.
