The school service staff union will sue the city for dismissals
The union, representing hundreds of school staff who lost seats last month, plans to sue the city on Wednesday, claiming that dismissals were unnecessary and discriminatory because of the disproportionate impact on schools where poor students study.
The trial is probably the last remedy available to the District Council's 37 trade union trying to cancel the dismissal.
Six hundred and seventy-two school assistants, parent coordinator and other employees who were among the lowest-paid workers in the city lost their seats on 7 October as a result of what union leaders described as a political response to their refusal to give the city access to medical funds managed by workers' groups to close a hole in the budget last spring.
City officials categorically rejected this accusation.
At the City Council hearings last month, school Chancellor Dennis M. Walcott said the layoffs were part of the budget they signed in June.
One of the board members argued, telling him that there was no indication in the budget that school support staff would be dismissed.
Representatives of the 37 district council reported that they had filed a complaint, warning the Department of Education that a lawsuit had been filed against him; a press conference would be held on Wednesday to declare a formal suit before the State Supreme Court in Manhattan.
The lawsuit will identify Mr. Walcott and the City's Department of Education as defendants and list eight temporarily dismissed employees as plaintiffs, all black or Latin American women, like most of the assistants who lost their seats.
Elizabeth Thomas, a representative of the city's legal department, said that the city had not seen the lawsuit and therefore could not comment on its specific provisions.
