Mission over, Congress ready for Libya agreement
It seems that the Republicans and Democrats on Capitol Hill are finally ready to agree to something related to the uprising in Libya.
All it took was for the mutiny to succeed, the long-time dictator Muammar Gaddafi was captured and killed, and the American intervention ended.
On Tuesday, the Senate Foreign Affairs Committee is to consider a resolution put forward by Chairman John Kerry (Democratic, Massachusetts) along with Senators John McCain (Republican, Arizona) and Joseph I. Lieberman (Independent, Connecticut), who praises Libyans for a successful rebellion and American troops for "the bravery".
"The point of this resolution is to honor the brave people of Libya as they begin to rebuild their country," Kerry said.
"This is confirmation of the support of both parties for their democratic aspirations".
Language may seem harmless, but no discussion on Libya has been easy.
This summer, legislators from both parties argued with each other and the White House about the language of a series of resolutions endorsing or condemning the role of the American army in NATO's mission in Libya.
In June, Kerry and McCain presented a resolution allowing limited use of American military forces in Libya.
The bill was rejected by the House of Representatives by a large majority vote of both parties and never reached the Senate.
But on the same day that the bill failed in the House of Representatives, the House also did not support a proposal that would cut funding for the American operation in Libya.
This left the American mission in some sort of legislative purgatory - when Congress is annoyed enough to criticize Obama's approach to the mission, but not so angry as to really tear the soil out of her feet.
Then the events surpassed Congress's indecision.
Tripoli surrendered to the Libyan rebels in August and Gaddafi was killed on 20 October.
The NATO mission officially concluded on 31 October.
Now the Senate can be ready to act.
The resolution of the Foreign Affairs Committee “rewards the Libyan people for their incredible bravery and extraordinary endurance in pursuit of freedom” and thanks the men and women of the United States Armed Forces and their coalition partners who participated in the military operation to protect the Libyan people for their extraordinary courage and professionalism”.
The resolution also “affirms the national interest of the United States in the successful and irreversible transition to democracy in Libya”.
Will the new measures receive the full support of the Foreign Affairs Council or break up legislators like the June bill?
The last version was opposed by Senator Richard G. Luger, Republican leader on the Committee.
Luger's spokesman said Monday that he had not yet seen the latest version of the bill.
On the other side of the Capitol, the House of Representatives this week should vote for a constitutional amendment requiring a balanced budget, the main legislative priority for almost every Republican and for some Democrats in Congress.
This measure, proposed by House Member Bob Goodlatt (Republican, Virginia), will be the first constitutional amendment on the budget or anything else to be put to a plenary vote by the Congress of that convocation.
Other legislators have not yet been able to bring their amendments to the plenary, but not because they have not tried.
The Goodlatt Amendment is only one of the 68 constitutional amendments addressing a wide range of issues that have been introduced in this convocation.
Some duplicated - the same bill was introduced in the House of Representatives and the Senate - others were minor variations among themselves.
There are at least 15 versions of the balanced budget amendments only in the House of Representatives and some more about “control over federal spending”.
Some of them are identical, but give their authors - mostly newly elected Republicans who wish to decorate their résumés - the opportunity to brag that they have “suggested” such a proposal.
The budget control act, which took place in August, required both the House of Representatives and the Senate to vote for a balanced budget amendment.
In March, 58 senators voted in favour of a non-binding resolution supporting such an amendment.
In addition to the budget, some Congressmen want to limit the number of terms of office for members of Congress, and House member José Serrano (Democratic, New York) wants to abolish the two-term limit for the president.
Congressman Jesse L. Jackson Jr. (Democrat, Illinois) has proposed numerous amendments that guarantee, among other things, the right to quality education and health care.
An amendment prohibiting same-sex marriage has been proposed for many years, as has another one prohibiting the burning of a flag.
Some legislators also want to allow the repeal of federal laws if two thirds of the states object to them.
As members of Congress have sought to propose amendments, they have not moved faster than in past years.
In the 111th Congress, legislators proposed 77 such amendments, while in the 110th Congress they introduced 66.
This pace is declining compared to the early 1990s, when members of Congress, according to the Senate Library, regularly proposed more than 150 amendments every two years.
But they were no more successful than they are now.
The last amendment that was adopted, the 27th, was approved in 1992, but it was actually introduced into Congress in 1789.
