Walls have eyes: How researchers study you on Facebook
Before becoming a new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Bering Brawick was an ordinary guy to articulate his anti-immigration views on the Internet.
On Monday, Brawick, who confessed to the Norwegian massacre in July, which claimed the lives of 77 people, appeared at his first public hearing.
Although Brawick could act alone, he was far from alone online: he spent a lot of time preparing to attack his computer, interacting with millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social media.
After the summer tragedy, researchers wanted to learn more about these people.
But how do we find them?
Easy, you just have to go to Facebook.
"We realized it's not hard to get close to them," says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recently published report on European cyber-populism by the British DEMOS Research Center.
The personal data stock on Facebook is so large, Bartlett says that researchers could easily use the website's promotional tool to single out the necessary demographic group with scientific accuracy - that marketers have been doing for several years.
Bartlett's team found half a million right-wing fans across Europe and then pitched them ads, but instead of showing a new group or diet product, the ad offered the user a poll that included questions about their level of education, attitudes to violence, and optimism about their own future.
With the help of Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 participants in 14 extreme right-wing parties in 11 European countries - even without leaving the office.
"It's a whole new way of doing research," Bartlett says.
Some results are less striking: right-wing online actors are more likely to be male youths dissatisfied with immigration.
But suddenly "those who combine their online activity with offline activity are more intelligent, more democratic and less aggressive than those who just hide behind the monitor."
The work of DEMOS is just one example of how Facebook becomes a new popular tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centres, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything in the world, from health issues to social trends, expressed in the Lights, posts on the wall and status updates.
With over 800 million active users adding an average of three entries per day, Facebook's "super-actual information" causes a research boom, increasing the number of scientific articles with the title of the site in the title by 800 per cent over the past five years.
For some researchers, Facebook's beauty is that it provides an opportunity to study people who cannot be approached on the street with a notebook.
"Once upon a time, if you wanted to interview people from the British National Party, it would be very difficult to identify them."
"You would have to join the party, and they would never have accepted you," Bartlett says.
"Facebook excludes all this - you address them directly".
Others say that the site could identify and investigate problems of social health.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues showed that students who discussed their drunken feats on Facebook were much more at risk of alcoholism than students who were silent about it.
Moreno suggests that students' peers, such as their hostel mentors, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student who too often updates drunken status.
"You cannot solve the problem without finding it," said Washington Post Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Moreno and director of the Center for Child Health, Behaviour and Development at Seattle Children's Research Institute.
"We have found a way to identify children at risk who would not otherwise be found."
Facebook also continuously retrieves different kinds of data about its users.
The website's data processing team processed statistics on relationship status and Valentine's Day, voter turnout in mid-2010, and the National Happiness Index (mostly using information only available to them - cyberfreedom champions have long insisted that the site should make its extensive data collection publicly available for research).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - in exchange for being able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, the site can process your personal data.
But what about when Facebook users become part of a study they don't even know about?
While researchers have strictly defined standards for offline research, online data are publicly available.
"I don't think many users have even thought about what a researcher can watch their profiles," says Neil Selwin, a sociologist from the London Knowledge Laboratory, about a study he conducted in 2006 using public Facebook pages of students.
"As far as they knew, it was just between them and their friends."
Then the question of methodology arises.
Even offline there is no guarantee that the object of the study is absolutely honest.
You can't find out on Facebook how much information in the profile and on the user page is true.
"What you're saying on Facebook and what you're doing outside Facebook are two completely different things," Selvin says.
That is why, despite his years of work in technology research, Selvin thinks that the notebook and pen are still the best research tools that can be used.
"Nothing can replace going out into the real world and communicating with real people," he says.
"Social research is supposed to be about social research, and most social research is still offline".
