Seven lessons from Steve Jobs' lost interview, which is shown at the theater this week.
After Steve Jobs' death on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, describing the technical genius as the Great Inventor of Modernity.
But what Apple fans might consider the biggest discovery in a recently discovered interview, which was remembered in the run-up to the major markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood in business processes and production technologies.
He was, of course, a designer, a dreamer and considered himself a hippie, but he was also a thorough organizer and a modernist of the production process who believed that many business leaders suffered from "diseases to think that a really great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] a great idea from a great product separates a great amount of skillful labor."
Back in 1995, Bob Kringley created the television series Triumph Nerds about the arrival of a personal computer, and he spent more than an hour with Jobs after a unique long conversation.
By then, it had been about 10 years since Jobs had been kicked out of Apple, and he had already worked hard for his new computer company NeXT in anticipation of the massive development of the Internet.
While a small part of Kringley's interview was used in the Nerds, he says the originals of the interview were missing during transportation.
It was only after Jobs' death that a full VHS copy was found in the director's garage.
This filmed material, slightly edited, was the basis for a 68-minute film, Steve Jobs: Lost interview, which is released at Landmark Theatres this Wednesday and Thursday.
For a man known for his hatred for a detailed interview, Jobs here seems unorthodox to articulate his technological philosophy and business strategies.
And incredibly thoughtful.
In four different points during the interview, there are long intervals between questions and answers - reflections of 10 to 15 seconds, where Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts to be more precise.
There are also moments where Jobs' perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems annoyed by Kringley's questions, forcing him to move faster to issues or phenomena of greater importance.
In the pre-Pixar era, iPods and iPhones lost interview there is something sinister prophetic when Jobs evaluates what he sees different companies doing right and wrong, and offers their own vision of the future of information technologies.
It's one thing to read about Jobs' posthumous assessments of work, but there's something vulnerable and inspiring in Jobs that we see here, an alarming dreamer on the threshold of greatness.
