How many lies do we face?
Within one day, studies show that you can be lied 10 to 200 times.
It is now assumed that much of this is a lie to save.
Another study revealed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting each other.
Discovering a lie or proving a lie is a necessary skill for each individual for both personal and professional purposes.
Unlike a room game like, say, charades, where you have to say, "Got caught!", lying is a serious direction of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities involved in comprehensive research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One result of the study is that most of the old myths about lies have been dispelled.
Liars look into the eyes.
They don't always stutter, stutter, blush or fuss.
There is no reason to conclude that liars are difficult to spot and difficult to expose.
An experienced liar can get to the truth by observing the structure of the allegations, the mimic, the structure of the questions, and the time characteristics.
I have spent several years exploring scientific discoveries in a vast and ever-increasing segment of knowledge of lies, and it is clear that the detection of lies is a modern skill that is easy to learn and helps guide our complex world -- especially if your professional responsibilities include recruitment, interview, negotiation or management.
Good liars are excellent at reading others, making them feel relaxed, managing their own emotions, and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from the study that extraverts lie more often than introverts, that men lie more about themselves, while women lie about others, usually to protect someone ' s feelings that married people lie less to their partners than unmarried ones (but that lie they say is most often brazen).
We also know that if you are perceived as a cheater, others will feel less guilty by deceiving you.
How do you know if anyone's lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your object.
It's called "the definition of the initial state."
This helps to provide a starting point for assessing changes further.
Observe the pose, the laughter, the vocal characteristics of your object.
You might want to know if a person knocks with his feet all the time in normal condition, then you will not be making unfair accusations when you see a knock with his feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for groups of deceptive verbal and non-verbal acts.
Treat these groups as red flags, not proof of deception.
Liars can fix the upper part of their body when trying to remember their history, they can put their feet towards the door, lean towards the exit, change their pose in a certain way, or display "facilitation after interview" -- this exaggerated sigh of relief and pose change when all the difficult questions are behind.
Investigators often falsify the end of interrogation signal just to see that relief after the interview.
