The Court will approve the “digital television transition” in Mexico in 2015
The replacement of analogue signals with digital ones is one of the most important changes the world has experienced in recent years.
The Supreme Court rejected the constitutional claims made by the Senate and the House of Representatives against the presidential decree, which transfers the so-called “digital television transition” from 2021 to 2015, as there were no eight votes required to annul it.
A minority of four ministers, including the president of the court, Juan Silva Mesa, considered that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his authority by issuing a decree detailing actions to move to digital terrestrial television.
As a result, constitutional claims made by the Senate were dismissed on the basis of the absence of a qualified majority of eight votes required for the court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and it remains in force.
The draft statement prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero proposed that the decree be declared unconstitutional because the regulation of the radio and television programme was a right enshrined by law in the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and legislative reserve.
Only Salvidar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sanchez Cordero voted in favour of the project.
On this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies held two constitutional debates to refute the decree and support the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions mentioned therein regarding the transition to digital broadcasting.
At the ministerial meeting, it was also decided to reject the request of the Chamber of Deputies without entering into a discussion of the draft, also under the responsibility of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister said that he disagreed with the arguments of the draft in the sense that the federal executive branch could not determine the general rules of the measure to be prepared by the public administration.
“I also do not believe that if it did, it would affect the autonomy of the regulator” and recalled that planning public policy in strategic areas such as telecommunications has to do with the federal executive, which has a constitutional mandate, the administration of the State.
The replacement of analogue signals with digital ones - one of the most important changes that have taken place in recent years - has led to better use of radio-electric spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
Postponing the transition, he said, would be to postpone the benefits of digitization, which includes meeting public needs, which have not only a technical dimension, "as it covers economic, social, political and national security issues."
These questions, he said, “requires the work of the entire system of public economic governance, which includes a group of authorities which the Constitution brings together in the executive branch of the State”.
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world had already completed the transition to digital broadcasting, and had done so with the assistance of the executive, despite the existence of highly specialized technical institutions.
It cannot be concluded from this that the Government, in adopting the decree under discussion, which in any event affects the competence of Congress, is enforcing the laws adopted by the Legislative Assembly in the administrative sphere, he said.
Michoacán analyzes the possibility of counting "voice by voice"
According to data transferred to the PDP, the difference between the first and second seats in the gubernatorial elections is only 27 per cent, even without counting the votes on 879 of the total of 6.074 protocols.
The ability to count “voice by vote” is real with regard to this year's electoral process in Michoacán, where, according to the Provisional Election Results Programme (PPRP), the difference between the first and second seats in the gubernatorial elections is only 27 per cent, even without counting the votes that are 879 out of the total of 6.074 protocols.
In the light of this, the President of the General Council of the Michoacán Electoral Institute (MCI), Maria de Los Angeles Lianderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on 9 November, the electorate had adopted a set of principles to harmonize local rules with federal electoral reform.
It should be recalled that Michoacán did not adopt the State Constitution or Electoral Code or the Electoral Law, as the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the legal time of their entry into force in this electoral process and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel did not include its publication within the time frame specified in the law in the State Official Gazette, stating that he had some objections.
On the same day, 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice (SJJ) ruled on a constitutional claim brought by the local legislature and called the state's constitutional reform representative's “valid and illegal” vote, as it had no right to “settling or supporting them”.
In an interview on the possibility of a “voice by vote”, Maria de los Ángeles Lünderal argued that, with the adoption of suitable principles by the General Council of the IWV, it would be possible to submit a partial or full count of votes to the local electoral body.
Thus, a partial recount of one or more ballot boxes may be made under the conditions that: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there is no record of voting and counting documents in the ballot box or is not in the possession of the chairman; or there are obvious errors or corrections in the record.
In addition, there may be a general recount of votes in all ballot boxes when there is a sign that the difference between the alleged winning candidate and the second ballot is less than or equal to one per cent, provided that there is a request at the beginning of the session from the party representative and/or the coalition that put out the second of the candidates mentioned.
A general recount will also be made if, at the end of the normal count, it is established that the difference between the winner and the second-placed candidate is less than or equal to 1 per cent, provided that there is a request from the political party whose candidate took second place, in the event that the ballot boxes that were counted in part are excluded.
It is worth noting that this is the case for the elections in Morelia, where according to the EDP, the difference between first and second place is only 0.16%, even excluding 129 votes out of a total of 923 protocols.
