A new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday
The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monty, will meet with the President of Italy tomorrow to introduce a new government that will face a crisis that has brought this country to the brink of economic disaster.
The appointed Italian Prime Minister, Mario Monty, will meet with the President of Italy on Wednesday to present a new government that will face a crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic disaster and has damaged the entire eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace stated that Monty, appointed on Sunday, would meet with the President, Giorgio Napolitano, on Wednesday to confirm that he could form a government.
He is expected to present a cabinet composed mainly of technocrats, although it is not clear when the new executive will take its position.
Monty said he would present to the President the results of his negotiations with the political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my full confidence in our country's ability to get out of this difficult period," the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monty did not make it clear that he was able to form a government, but the tone of his comments showed that the obstacles had been overcome.
"Structure is now well-defined," he said.
Monty completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than usual, as Italy was grappling with the political and financial crisis that put their debt at a critical level
The Administration, under the leadership of former European Commissioner Monty, must approve the austerity package required by European leaders in order to restore confidence in Italy.
Based on pressure on Monty to hurry, unstable markets set the income from Italy's BTP bonds 10 years above 7 per cent, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to save.
Emma Marchegalia, the leader of the Italian Employers Federation, told reporters after meeting Monty, "We said we would actively support this government."
We believe that this Government is Italy's last chance to emerge from this critical situation.
Monty's chances of success were largely based on the support of the LDP party Silvio Berlusconi, who was forced to resign on Saturday due to the crisis.
"We believe that Professor Monty's efforts should lead to a good outcome," said reporters Angelino Alphano, secretary of the centrist-right party.
The support of the LDP, the largest party in Italy, is important because so far many of its members have opposed the government majority of technocrats that form Monty.
Parliamentary support
The new Monty government should have strong parliamentary support for reforms that are likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blocking or suspension of these attempts could lead to a new and destructive attack on financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks increased pressure, warning that Monty's failure could be a disaster.
Monty began his consultations on Monday with political parties, unions and business groups, as well as youth and women's organizations.
He'll end up meeting on Tuesday night.
Monty was appointed on Sunday Napolitano, which allowed an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief hiatus at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would retire, Italy's debt value has now reached a critical level against the backdrop of uncertainty as to whether the new Prime Minister would be successful.
Saving Italy with a public debt of 1.8 billion euros would be too much for the eurozone’s modern financial defenders.
Monty said that his government would exist until the next elections scheduled for 2013, despite widespread projections that politicians would only give him time to reform before setting up a new election.
Monty said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist that it should be composed only of technical specialists, evidence of their dissatisfaction with the financial situation affecting the process.
Political sources have reported that mutual mistrust and disagreement between parties complicate the attempt to include political figures.
