A trip to Costa Rica is a dream come true.'
In an exclusive interview with Viva bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam said the band was ready to give one of the best concerts the following Sunday at the National Stadium.
There have been more than 20 years of waiting, but the group says it is also a dream for them that has become a reality, to play in this country.
This was a statement by bassist and founder, Jeff Ament, who gave an exclusive interview to Viva from Brazil last week.
The group is in South America on a 20th anniversary tour and will make its only stop in Central America on Sunday, the 20th.
On that day, they will perform at the National Stadium, starting at 7:30 p.m., along with a team from Los Angeles The X and a local band, Las Robertas.
This is a passage from a conversation that is fully deciphered online in The Nation.
For your Costa Rican fans, is this a real dream that Pearl Jam will play in Costa Rica?
A trip to Costa Rica is a dream come true for us, too.
This is just our second visit to South and Central America, and so far it's going well.
I've only been to Costa Rica once-- on vacation, it's a beautiful country, and I think we can stay there for a few days.
That's why we're very happy to bring our music there.
I ask that because there is some loyalty to the group; fans live in tension the days before the concert.
What do you say to your most devoted fans?
Thank you for being with us all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica, thanks for waiting so long, and we're sorry it took us so long to get here.
Some people, waiting for your concert, treat him like the biggest show of the year.
Does this add a little tension to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we've played over the past 21 years have been in the last two weeks.
We've had some great shows in San Paulo, and we hope it's got us in shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
We really want to play here.
We love this country, we love surfing and the jungle, as far as these two things are concerned, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you know about Costa Rica and its surf waves?
We have a lot of surfing friends, and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarindo, and the waves here are incredible.
My friends always go surfing in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, as well as Mexico, these are great surfing places, that's how we learned about it, from people who love surfing.
Looking at the tour, you can say you made grand shows with a lot of songs.
What did you plan for your performance in Costa Rica?
Since we've never played there before, we have no limits on what we can do.
We'll try to make the best show possible with a variety of songs; we'll try to play a few songs from each album and present our fans with a great variety of repertoires.
You never repeat the repertoire.
How does that work?
I think it's partly because we have nine records and we can play more than 120 songs, and everyone likes different songs, so it's hard to choose which songs to play every night.
When we have two or three songs that we haven't played for a while, it keeps us in a tone and surprises us because it reminds us of the reasons why we loved those songs and what we might have forgotten.
It makes the show more interesting to us and so I think it makes it more interesting to people.
On this tour, you celebrate 20 years of your career.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you've done?
Yes, absolutely.
First of all, I think none of us could ever imagine that we'd be in a rock band and that we've been doing this for more than 20 years makes it look like a dream.
We rejoice in our luck, and we are very encouraged that we can continue to make music together.
We all love each other and love to make music.
We're happy to travel to places in the world we've always wanted to go.
Things are going very well for us.
What does it mean for you to be a significant part of the grunge's bloom?
It has always been an honour to be part of this group of great collectives.
We're good friends with the guys from Soundgarden, Mudhoney, and Alice in Chains.
It's great when the movement grows out of a group of friends, and that's unusual.
From time to time, one group from the same city appears, but much more strange when five or ten groups appear at the same time in the same city.
We're proud and honored to be part of the Seattle band.
I still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden during their tour, so we're happy to be friends with all of them and we're honored to be part of Seattle's sound that came out.
It's also very strange that a group like yours stays together and in the same lineup for so long.
Yeah, four of us were together for 21 years, and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is much longer than many groups exist.
First, I think we're lucky we're still alive, and secondly, we care about others.
We are all very close friends and, as a result, music roads have also been opened that give everyone the freedom to experiment.
We trust each other's music, and it couldn't have been better.
Your attitude to the word of glory was difficult; but thanks to your success, you were able to do whatever you wanted.
How do you find balance?
When we grew up, it became easier to strike a balance.
We care not to be on the tour too long, because it's easy to get into this game of big crowds and people who love your music.
As long as you remember that people are here for music, it reminds you that you have to respect music and what made it without deciding to be famous and be a rock star, something that none of us really care about.
How do you remember your other project, Mother Love Bone?
I think we're writing really good songs and it was great at the beginning.
We've been a band for almost three years and we haven't released a single album, until Andy's death (Andrew Woods).
There were a lot of disappointments because it's been so long, and most important that we're still close friends with Bruce (Ferweser) and Greg (Gilmore), who started with us in the band, and when I hear a song or see a picture, I think about the incredible man Andy was, and how he made me laugh, it's always been a pleasure to go to work, laugh, talk about music and football, and a lot of other things.
He was a wonderful man, and we miss him.
The local band Las Robertas will be responsible for opening the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you're familiar with her work, especially Eddie Wedder, and that's why you chose her to open it?
Yeah, the producers sent us some video offers, and it was the band we liked the most, so we're looking forward to seeing what Las Robertas can offer in person, and it's got to be very exciting.
Why do you keep changing the words in Yellow Ledbetter at concerts?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Wedder), so I don't know.
He sings it, and I think he's using the first thing that comes to his mind.
Who influenced you as a bass player?
There's so many of them.
Among the first to come to mind, Gizer Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramon, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many of them that I can talk all day about bassists I love.
How did Pearl Jam succeed in maintaining the relevance of the grunge even though he is no longer in fashion?
I think we all feel a bit detached from the word grunge.
When I think about him, he reminds me of the bands I mentioned earlier, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana, and everyone who appeared at the same time, and if that's important now, I think it's wonderful, because it's music that's worth listening to, and teams like Mudhoney make music now better than ever.
At first, your music was darker, and now it's more positive.
How do you explain this change?
That's interesting, because I think there are a few songs on the album that may seem easier, but there are songs like The End or Just Breathe that are considered very grim, although they may sound a little positive.
From both, when Ed played them, I cried when I listened to them, these songs were very dark.
I think that when you grow up and there was some trauma in your life and you lost a family member or a friend, these events start to affect your creativity and your music, and these two songs, of course, reflect that for me.
So, I think you can be a happy person and still be able to make dark music.
