MSS announces the Obese gene search program
Social protection leads research on finding obesity in children and young people; it is supported by IPN experts
The Mexican Institute for Social Protection (MSSI) has announced that it is conducting a study to detect obesity in children and young people, known as the protocol “Genetics of obesity in childhood and adolescence”, which will provide an estimate of the signs of overweight.
In his statement, Miguel Cruz López, Head of the Biochemistry Research Unit of the National Twenty-first Century Specialized Hospital, explained that a multidisciplinary team of therapists, nurses, dietologists and social workers had been assembled.
The team is assisted by specialists and graduate students from the National Institute of Health (NIPH) and the Centre for Scientific Research and Higher Education (CINVESTAV) of the National Polytechnic Institute (NPI).
The study invites the public (written or not) to participate by going to MSSI sports centres participating in the study to the Mexico Valley, where tests with children will be conducted every Saturday morning at 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol had begun at the Cuautemoke Sports Centre (in western Mexico State) and that since 8 October events had been held at the Nesaualcootle Sports Centre (in eastern Mexico State).
Once the target of 500 to 600 children has been achieved, the study will continue at the Independence Sports Centre (South Mexico City) and finally at the Morelos Sports Centre (North Mexico City).
He explained that the aim of the study was to understand the components and importance of genetics in relation to obesity development and to establish a risk factor among children and young Mexicans in order to prevent the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
The World Diabetes Day will be observed on 14 November, and the main objective will be to gather 3,000 children and adolescents between the ages of 6 and 14 with parental permission and supervision to complete individual nutrition questionnaires.
They will also be asked about physical activity and the history of family inherited diseases in order to avoid risk factors that lead to diseases such as diabetes or renal failure.
He explained that anthropometric measurements of all participants (weight, height and waist grip), blood pressure and glucose levels, fats, cholesterol and insulin, and genetic analysis (to identify genes associated with childhood obesity) would be conducted on Saturday.
Cruz Lopez said that the study reflected the concern of health professionals about the alarming increase in the weight of children.
Medical studies conducted between 1999 and 2006 indicate that there has been an increase in just six years: 77 per cent of boys were obese, 47 per cent of girls; and there has also been a significant increase in overweight," said MSSI.
He said that the justification for looking for markers was based on the fact that the population was different from other peoples in its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican was 65 per cent American Indian, 30 per cent European and five per cent African, a condition that affected genes associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that the main effect of obesity genetics is the body's inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and it is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit to participants was a comprehensive assessment of children, which could determine whether they had any excess weight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark folds on the neck (acants) and forearms means the likelihood of metabolism being violated and even prediabetes.
The information is given in full confidentiality and is transmitted in writing to the parents, to whom they explain all the measurements and changes in lifestyle that must be made to avoid the disease.
Cruz Lopez explained that there were three main reasons for overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: sitting lifestyle, or lack of daily physical activity, spending most of the day at home in front of television, and using transport at short distances instead of walking.
This is also due to high calorie consumption, i.e. increased consumption of sweet drinks and carbohydrates (taleh, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with large fat and protein content and genetic predisposition analysed in this program.
UNAM asphalt can avoid cracks
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, developed a polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture of best quality resistant to environmental and temperature effects.
If attention were paid to road-cover signals, it would be necessary to repair about 200,000 pits for each rainy season in the metropolitan area of Mexico City, says Rafael Herrera Nahera, researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, and adds that if the construction and maintenance of the paved road surface is correct, the number of pits can be reduced or even reduced to zero.
His lecture The technological perspective on pits read within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry reports that the laboratory for which he is responsible develops polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture with characteristics close to bitumen but with better resistance both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nahera said that this type of modified bitumen could be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, as in some cities in the north, to improve the quality of roads and therefore resist the formation of pits.
He explained that the bitumen, the hardest part of the oil, was the sequence of hydrocarbon molecules, some high molecular mass called asphalts, and others low molecular mass called Maltens, which together gave road coverage to its characteristic viscous behaviour.
The viscous behavior of bitumen is the fact that at high temperatures of about 180 degrees it behaves like liquid at 120 its viscosity is very high, and at 50 degrees Celsius it retains a near solid state, while at very low temperatures the bitumen becomes fragile, he said.
This means that street asphalt resistance is not constant, but changes during the day, depending on natural conditions and temperature, said a specialist in chemical engineering.
A chemical scientist observed that the streets of Mexico City were mostly covered with flexible coating, which was made up of six layers of material, of which the last three included bitumen.
Among the uppermost layers is a bitumen made of small stones dropped into the bitumen and then compressed.
Every stone that makes up this coating, he said, is in bitumen.
When driving and working, this helps the forces to spread very well on the road surface.
If it were modified asphalt, they would be distributed even better, said the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt surface, he added, there is a last layer, which is called a layer of wear, which is made of a small stone, actually sand also immersed in asphalt.
As it is a layer that will contact the wheels of transport, it should have more resistance than asphalt coating and provide road friction.
As part of the road surface that will receive and distribute these forces, the wear layer also requires adequate thickness and the material from which it is made must be taken into account.
The weather, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are also very important factors for consideration, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the condition of the asphalt.
When the ground is raw, the water penetrates the surface and it is difficult for it to get out of it, it softens all the layers of the surface and hence the formation of pits.
In creating pits, he said, the wear layer first wears out and only then affects bitumen, but damage does not occur instantly, which should be addressed at the first signs of maintenance programmes.
A member of the National Research System also explained that transport load is another important factor in the formation of holes, and therefore the thickness of each layer of coating must always be linked to traffic load and this requirement must be guaranteed in order to prevent the frequent appearance of pits.
Rafael Herrera said that relatively bitumen still has a lot to study and do, for example, bitumen emulsions, which in other countries are already on the market and even help fix pits with ease and without the use of high temperatures.
