Introduction of a “gold rule” budget in the Constitution
The leadership of the great coalition of Social Democrats and Christian Democrats in power in Austria decided to write a budget “gold rule” in the constitution on Tuesday to reduce the budget deficit and thus avoid possible downgrading of Austria's state credit rating by rating agencies (troika A).
Social Democrat Chancellor Werner Faymann himself announced this decision at the end of the Council of Ministers meeting, with Austrian public debt at 74.6%, significantly higher than the upper threshold of 60% set by the Maastricht Treaty but lower than the public debt of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
If Austria's capacity to pay fell by only one point, from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay interest of €3,000 million more each year, the argument of Vice Chancellor and Foreign Minister Michael Spindelegger of Christian Democrats.
Austria thus fulfils the Eurozone summit demand on 26 October in Brussels; the Heads of State and Government demanded a reduction in budget deficits by the end of 2012 and a return to balanced government accounts through a constitution or equivalent law.
The Austrian Government's decision resembled the “German model”, since Germany was the first European country to adopt this “rule”.
Until 2017, the structural deficit of the State budget should be reduced by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year, and since 2017 the structural deficit of the State budget of the federal State should not exceed 0.35% of GDP in any year, and land, like communes, should represent balanced budgets.
The goal is to make the public debt fall below the 60% set by the Maastricht Treaty by 2020/2021.
