The immigration policy under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized on various sides - the overloading of police, judicial and administrative services subordinated to the policy of numbers and the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of France as a “human rights State”.
Then there was the administrative harassment of foreign students, which came into the news when the Minister of the Interior (Liberación of 23 May) stated that France "does not need foreign talents, masons and waiters".
But it is very rarely analyzed from an economic point of view.
There is much agreement between the right and the left on this issue.
The right-wing tone was set by Jacques Chirac, who in 1976 stated that “900,000 unemployed will not be a problem in a country with 2 million foreign workers” and by Michel Rocar, on the left, who explained in 1990 that France “can't accept the poor from all over the world”.
The only difference is in the level of generosity.
In 2005, the fear of an invasion of the country by a Polish plumber was felt by both the left and right.
Both sides see the burden of immigration on the French economy and on French society.
The only difference is the level of generosity that they would be willing to show to immigrants.
In its programme, François Hollande limited himself to the banality of saying that “joint work will solve our immigration problem”.
This perception of immigration as a burden and a problem may offer an electoral advantage, but it is economically costly.
As economists Ian Goldin and Jeffrey Cameron remind us in a recent book summarizing recent immigration data (Special People: How Migration Formed Our World and Defined Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among professionals about the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries that accept immigrants.
Limiting immigration reduces growth and reduces employment.
Fear of the influence of immigrants is based on the notion that they are able to replace local workers, especially low-skilled workers, by triggering wage declines.
But experience has shown that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than replacing local labour with jobs that lack local labour.
Unskilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract local labour and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training is not related to job offers.
Positive impact on wages
Just as it would be difficult for a surgeon to work in a country where there is a shortage of anesthesiologists, the complementarity between local and immigrant workers leads to a positive effect on the wages of local workers.
Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1% increase in migration flows results in an increase of 0.6-0.9% in real long-term wages.
This is without taking into account the fact that the diversity contributed by immigrants contributes to the creation of new ideas and economic growth (among the United States Nobel Prize winners is a large proportion of naturalized immigrants, and Google, Intel, Paypal and Yahoo were all founded by immigrants).
Migrants also make a net profit in social security systems, accounting for an average of 1 per cent of the total budgets of European countries.
The World Labour Organization estimates that, for example, in Germany, an immigrant who arrives at the age of 30 will generate a net return (income minus expenditure) on average of 150,000 euros in his or her life.
Nicolas Sarkozy, at the beginning of her mandate, was about to get "tooths" into the missing growth points.
These teeth, which were used to deter immigrants, had exactly the opposite effect.
