Rather, they have low qualifications: 80 per cent have no bachelor ' s degree, and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very common, at 85 per cent for persons with disabilities, compared with 38 per cent on average.
In short, these are all criteria that make it very difficult to get back to work and which are at the heart of the problem," says Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association established in 1992 to help companies hire a disabled worker.
Here are some of the obstacles.
